"Levy O., Rosenfeld M., Yam R., Shemesh A.","Heterogeneity of coral skeletons isotopic compositions during the 1998 bleaching event",2006,"Limnology and Oceanography","51","2",,"1142","1148",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33645079634&partnerID=40&md5=638de8ae0622ea75638ae98fba031f51","Department of Environmental Sciences and Energy Research, Weizmann Institute of Science, Rehovot 76100, Israel","Levy, O., Department of Environmental Sciences and Energy Research, Weizmann Institute of Science, Rehovot 76100, Israel; Rosenfeld, M., Department of Environmental Sciences and Energy Research, Weizmann Institute of Science, Rehovot 76100, Israel; Yam, R., Department of Environmental Sciences and Energy Research, Weizmann Institute of Science, Rehovot 76100, Israel; Shemesh, A., Department of Environmental Sciences and Energy Research, Weizmann Institute of Science, Rehovot 76100, Israel","The vulnerability of coral reefs to climate change, such as regional warming, became fully evident during the strong 1997-1998 El Niño event. This El Niño episode was associated with elevated sea-surface temperatures and caused mass mortality throughout many of the world's coral reefs. We analyzed the isotopic manifestation of this event in six Porites sp. coral skeletons from different localities in a small atoll (Alphonse) at the Seychelles Island. The aim was to validate the use of coral stable isotope compositions as recorders of such events in the past. The coupling between local-scale environment and global warming was weaker then expected, with regional warming being evident only when data from five colonies were averaged. Local conditions had a large effect on the isotopic compositions of coral skeletons. We conclude that future paleoclimate reconstructions, especially those attempts to identify past El Niño events, must be based on more than a single coral record. Moreover, the strong effect of local habitat on the isotopic composition of Porites sp. has to be considered when interpreting δ13C and δ18O records. © 2006, by the American Society of Limnology and Oceanography, Inc.",,"climate change; coral bleaching; coral reef; El Nino; isotopic composition; paleoclimate; Indian Ocean; Indian Ocean islands; Seychelles; Anthozoa; Porites",,,,,,"Abram, N.J., Gagan, M.K., McCulloch, M.T., Chappell, J., Hantoro, W.S., Coral reef death during the 1997 Indian Ocean dipole linked to Indonesian wildfires (2003) Science, 301, pp. 952-955; Aronson, R.B., Precht, W.F., Toscano, M.A., Koltes, K.H., The 1998 bleaching event and its aftermath on a coral reef in Belize (2002) Mar. Biol., 141, pp. 435-447; Barnes, D.J., Lough, J.M., Skeletons: Storage and recovery of environmental information (1996) Global Change Biol., 2, pp. 569-582; Taylor, R.B., Lough, J.M., Measurement of luminescence in coral skeletons (2003) J. Exp. Mar. Biol. Ecol., 295, pp. 91-106; Berkelmans, R., Oliver, J.K., Large scale bleaching on the Great Barrier Reef (1999) Coral Reefs, 18, pp. 55-60; Chalker, B.E., Barnes, D.J., Gamma densitometry for the measurement of coral skeletal density (1990) Coral Reefs, 4, pp. 95-100; Charles, C.D., Hunter, D.E., Fairbanks, R.G., Interaction between the ENSO and the Asian monsoon in a coral record of tropical climate (1997) Science, 277, pp. 925-928; Cobb, K.M., Charles, C.D., Cheng, H., Edwards, R.L., El Niño/Southern Oscillation and tropical Pacific climate during the last millennium (2003) Nature, 424, pp. 271-276; Cole, J.E., Dunbar, R.B., McClanahan, T.R., Muthiga, N.A., Tropical Pacific forcing of decadal SST variability in the Western Indian Ocean over the past two centuries (2000) Science, 287, pp. 617-619; Coles, S.L., Brown, B.E., Coral bleaching - Capacity for acclimatization and adaptation (2003) Adv. Mar. Biol., 46, pp. 183-223; Fritts, H.C., (1976) Tree Rings and Climate, , Academic Press, New York. [Reprinted 2001. Blackburn Press, Caldwell, New Jersey.]; Gagan, M.K., Ayliffe, L.K., Beck, J.W., Cole, J.E., Druf